name: Lorenz Attractor
description: The Lorenz attractor is a system of differential equations that models atmospheric convection and exhibits chaotic behavior—that is, sensitivity to initial conditions. It was introduced by Edward Lorenz in 1963 as a simplified model of weather. 🧮 The Equations (Lorenz System) The Lorenz system is a set of three coupled, nonlinear differential equations: 𝑑 𝑥 𝑑 𝑡 = 𝜎 ( 𝑦 − 𝑥 ) 𝑑 𝑦 𝑑 𝑡 = 𝑥 ( 𝜌 − 𝑧 ) − 𝑦 𝑑 𝑧 𝑑 𝑡 = 𝑥 𝑦 − 𝛽 𝑧 dt dx ​   dt dy ​   dt dz ​   ​    =σ(y−x) =x(ρ−z)−y =xy−βz ​   🧷 Parameters σ (sigma) – the Prandtl number (related to fluid viscosity); typical value: σ = 10 ρ (rho) – the Rayleigh number (related to temperature difference); typical value: ρ = 28 β (beta) – a geometric factor; typical value: β = 8/3 🌀 Key Properties Chaotic dynamics: Tiny differences in starting conditions lead to drastically different outcomes—a hallmark of chaos theory. Strange attractor: The trajectory never repeats and never settles to a fixed point or cycle, but remains within a bounded region that resembles butterfly wings. Fractal structure: The attractor has a fractal dimension; it's not just a surface or a curve, but something in between.
